# =============================================================================

# OBJECTIVE

# =============================================================================

#

# In the previous phases, all microservices were deployed successfully inside

# the Kubernetes cluster using ClusterIP Services.

#

# ClusterIP Services can communicate with each other inside the cluster through

# CoreDNS, but they cannot be accessed directly from outside the cluster.

#

# The objective of this phase is:

#

# • Install NGINX Ingress Controller using Helm.

# • Configure a common Ingress for all microservices.

# • Expose services to external clients (Postman/Browser).

# • Prepare the project for future Spring Cloud Gateway integration.

#

# =============================================================================

# CURRENT ARCHITECTURE

# =============================================================================

#

# External Client

# (Browser / Postman)

# │

# │

# NGINX Ingress

# (Controller)

# │

# -------------------------------------------------

# │                    │                        │

# ▼                    ▼                        ▼

# ms-transaction-       ms-wallet          ms-notification

# orchestrator

# │                    │                        │

# ▼                    ▼                        ▼

# ClusterIP Service   ClusterIP Service    ClusterIP Service

# │                    │                        │

# ▼                    ▼                        ▼

# Kubernetes Pods

#

#

# NOTE

# ----

# Ingress never communicates directly with Pods.

# It always forwards the request to a Kubernetes Service.

# The Service then forwards the request to one of the available Pods.

#

# =============================================================================

# WHY INGRESS?

# =============================================================================

#

# Before Ingress:

#

# • Pods have dynamic IP addresses.

# • ClusterIP Services are reachable only inside the cluster.

# • External clients cannot access ClusterIP Services directly.

#

# Ingress provides:

#

# • One entry point for the Kubernetes cluster.

# • URL/path-based routing.

# • Host-based routing.

# • HTTPS/TLS support.

# • Reverse proxy functionality.

#

# =============================================================================

# INSTALLING NGINX INGRESS USING HELM

# =============================================================================

#

# Instead of applying Kubernetes manifests manually, the Ingress Controller

# was installed using Helm.

#

# Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes.

#

# We are using Helm because:

#

# • It is the industry standard.

# • Frequently asked in interviews.

# • Used by Argo CD.

# • Easy to upgrade.

# • Easy to uninstall.

# • Easy to customize using values.yaml.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 1 : Verify Helm Installation

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm version

#

# Example Output:

#

# version.BuildInfo{

# Version:"v4.2.2"

# }

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 2 : Verify Kubernetes Cluster

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# kubectl cluster-info

#

# Verify:

#

# • Kubernetes API Server is running.

# • CoreDNS is running.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 3 : Verify Kubernetes Node

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# kubectl get nodes

#

# Verify:

#

# • Node status is Ready.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 4 : Verify Existing Helm Releases

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm list -A

#

# Before installation:

#

# No Helm releases should be present.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 5 : Add Helm Repository

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm repo add ingress-nginx https://kubernetes.github.io/ingress-nginx

#

# Purpose:

#

# Adds the official NGINX Helm repository.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 6 : Update Repository

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm repo update

#

# Purpose:

#

# Downloads the latest chart information.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 7 : Search Repository

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm search repo ingress-nginx

#

# Purpose:

#

# Verify that the repository contains the required chart.

#

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Step 8 : Install NGINX Ingress Controller

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#

# Command:

#

# helm install ingress-nginx ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx \

# --namespace ingress-nginx \

# --create-namespace

#

# Helm automatically created:

#

# • Namespace

# • Deployment

# • ReplicaSet

# • Service

# • Admission Service

# • ServiceAccount

# • RBAC Resources

# • ConfigMaps

# • Secrets

#

# All required Kubernetes resources were created automatically.

#

# =============================================================================

# HELM VERIFICATION COMMANDS

# =============================================================================

#

# Verify Helm Release

#

# helm list -A

